the nuclearly localized SKN7 does not itself respond to the oxidant but simply cooperates with YAP1 when it translocates to the nucleus. SKN7 undergoes a posttranslational modification by phosphorylation following exposure to oxidant. PMID:9811878 SFL1 is a transcriptional repressor of FLO11 that is needed for this mode of growth. However, since TPK2 inhibits SFL1 by phosphorylating it, FLO11 repression gets reliened and thus yeast can go for this mode upon nutrient starvation. Interaction of TPK2 with SFL1, a transcriptional repressor of FLO11, positively regulates FLO11 transcription. PMID:11399075 Here, we demonstrate that Sfl1 is present at specific regions on the promoters of several Ssn6-Tup1 regulated genes, and that in vitro PKA phosphorylation of Sfl1 inhibits DNA binding. We show that a tpk2Delta mutation increases the level of interaction between Sfl1 and DNA in vivo, suggesting a link between intracellular cAMP signaling and Sfl1/Ssn6-Tup1-mediated transcriptional repression.

PMID:9501067 PMID:12808050 STE5 must oligomerize in order to function. Increasing the pool of STE5 oligomers increases association with Ste11. Remarkably, STE5 oligomers are also more efficiently exported from the nucleus, retained in the cytoplasm by STE 11 and better recruited to the plasma membrane, resulting in constitutive activation of the mating mitogen-activated protein kinase cascade. Major form of STE 5 is an inactive monomer with an inaccessible RING-H2 domain and STE 11 binding site, whereas the active form is an oligomer that is more efficiently exported and recruited. PMID:12808050 STE5 forms dimers or higher order oligomers based on interallelic complementation, two-hybrid analysis, and coprecipitation. oligomerization of STE5 positively regulates all of these events and that the activation of STE5 involves a conformational switch from an inactive monomer to an active dimer.

PMID:9632750 Phosphorylation of FAR1 by the MAPK FUS3 causes it to interact with the G1-specific CDK complexes as a result of which they get inhibited and cell gets arrested in G1. Thus FAR1 is a CDK inhibitor which is phosphorylated by FUS3 but not KSS1. Far1 is regulated by positive and negative phosphorylation events. Pheromone treatment results in the activation of the Fus3 kinase, which in turn causes the phosphorylation of Far1 at T306 and possibly at T63 (left diagram). This phosphorylation event is necessary for the binding of Far1 to the Cln2- Cdc28 kinase. This interaction results into the functional inactivation of the Cln2-Cdc28 cell cycle-promoting activity and results into a G1 cell cycle arrest

PMID:9632750 In order to make sure that FAR1 exerts its effect only in G1, many mechanisms are involved. FAR1 is proteolysed in all phases of the cell cycle outside G1. This is done by the CDC28 kinases Cdc28-dependent S87 phosphorylation counteracts Far1 activation by targeting the protein for destruction. As a consequence, negative regulation on the Cln2-Cdc28 complex is alleviated and critical phosphorylation events needed for cell cycle progression can be executed. PMID:11395421

PMID:8707846 The a-factor receptor (Ste3p) is one of two pheromone receptors in the yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae that enable the cell-cell communication of mating. In this report, we show that this receptor is subject to two distinct covalent modifications-phosphorylation and ubiquitination. In cells mutant for two E2 activities, i.e., ubc4 delta ubc5 delta cells, the receptor was found to be substantially less ubiquitinated, and in addition, receptor turnover was slowed, suggesting that Ubc4p and Ubc5p may play a role in the recognition of the receptor protein as substrate for the ubiquitin system.
